<h2>String handling</h2><p>As well as numbers there are strings. <span style="color:#660000"><strong>E</strong></span><span style="color:#000066"><strong>asy</strong></span><span style="color:#660000"><strong>C</strong></span><span style="color:#000066"><strong>oder</strong></span> has a useful set of string handling commands that are needed when processing textual data received from the Internet. I&#39;ll show you some of the simpler ones, but be aware there are more powerful commands that must be left for a later tutorial.</p><p>Copy this code to the editor:</p><p style="text-align:center"> </p><div id="clear" style="display:none">n</div><div id="code">yes</div><p style="margin-left:40px; text-align:center"><a href="#" id="copy">Copy to editor</a></p><div style="color:#660000; display:none; font-family:&quot;Courier New&quot;,Courier,monospace"><a href="#" id="copy">Copy to editor</a></div><p>In the Values section of the Core package in our Programmers Reference, you&#39;ll find a number of other functions that deal with strings. Try experimenting with a few of them.</p><h2>Next: <a href="#" id="next">Introducing the DOM</a></h2>